Project Description – Image classification using CNNs in Keras¶

Context:¶

Can you differentiate a weed from a crop seedling?The ability to do so effectively can mean better crop yields and better stewardship of the environment.The Aarhus University Signal Processing group, in collaboration with University of Southern Denmark, has recently released a dataset containing images of unique plants belonging to 12 species at several growth stages.

Data Description:¶

We are provided with a dataset of images of plant seedlings at various stages of growth. Each image has a filename that is its unique id. The dataset comprises 12 plant species. The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from a photo.

Dataset:¶

The data file names are:

  • images.npy
  • Label.csv

Objective:¶

To build a convolution neural network that is capable of determining a plant's species from a photo

Loose Silky-bent has the highest number of images in the data set while Common wheat and Maize are jointly the lowest in number among the plants in the data set. This is an imbalanced data and models tend to have bias towards the dorminant classes. Undersampling or oversampling may help to correct such bias. However, we will pass the data the way it is into our model in this project.

  plt.title(f' {title}')
  plt.show()

It can be observed that the leaf shapes and structure are the major differenciating factors among the plant species in the data. Proper classification of these plant species by our model will depend on how well these differenciating factors are learnt.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

In [11]:
#Let's plot the pixel intensity histogram of image of a sample from each plant specie in the data set
def images_int(data, title):
  plt.hist(data.ravel(), bins=256, range=[0, 256], color='crimson')
  plt.title(f'Histogram Showing Pixel Intensities And Counts of {title}', color='crimson')
  plt.ylabel("Number Of Pixels Belonging To The Pixel Intensity", color="crimson")
  plt.xlabel("Pixel Intensity", color="crimson")
  plt.show()
SFC = images_int(x[0], 'Small-flowered Cranesbill')
FH = images_int(x[496], 'Fat Hen')
SP = images_int(x[971], 'Sheperds Purse')

CH = images_int(x[2034], 'Charlock')
CL = images_int(x[2424], 'Cleavers')
SM = images_int(x[2711], 'Scentless Mayweed')
SB = images_int(x[3227], 'Sugar beet')
MZ = images_int(x[3612], 'Maize')
BG = images_int(x[3833], 'Black-grass')
LSB = images_int(x[4096], 'Loose Silky-bent')

Data Preprocessing¶

We shall perform the following operations on the images and print some samples before and after the preprocessing

  • Guassian blurring -Convert image from RGB to HSV -Apply closing opration(one of mophological opration) -Apply segmentation -Normalisation of the images
In [14]:
new_train = []
sets = []; getEx = True
for i in x:
    blurr = cv2.GaussianBlur(i,(5,5),0)
    hsv = cv2.cvtColor(blurr,cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV) #Using BGR TO HSV conversion. 
    lower = (25,40,50)
    upper = (75,255,255)
    mask = cv2.inRange(hsv,lower,upper) # create a mask 
    struc = cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_ELLIPSE,(11,11)) #getting structring element ( kernel) of sie 11x11
    mask = cv2.morphologyEx(mask,cv2.MORPH_CLOSE,struc) # applying morphological transformation ( closing operation ) to remove imperfections from the binary image ( mask)
    boolean = mask>0
    new = np.zeros_like(i,np.uint8)
    new[boolean] = i[boolean]
    new_train.append(new)
    if getEx:
        plt.subplot(2,3,1);plt.imshow(i) # ORIGINAL
        plt.subplot(2,3,2);plt.imshow(blurr) # BLURRED
        plt.subplot(2,3,3);plt.imshow(hsv) # HSV CONVERTED
        plt.subplot(2,3,4);plt.imshow(mask) # MASKED
        plt.subplot(2,3,5);plt.imshow(boolean) # BOOLEAN MASKED
        plt.subplot(2,3,6);plt.imshow(new) # NEW PROCESSED IMAGE
        plt.show()
        getEx = False
new_train = np.asarray(new_train)

Model 2: CNN with Dropout after Convolution and having two Dense layers with 32 & 24 units respectively

Since CNN Model 1 does not appear to have good validation accuracy and appears to be overfitting on the training dataset, let's use CNN Model 2, which has a different architecture and see whether that will generalize well and not overfit.

In [29]:
#Setting the structure for model_2
class conv_Layers:

  def __init__(self, nfilters, kernel_size, stride=1, 
               pool_size=2, leakyrelu_slope=0.1, dropc=0.0, bnorm=False):
    self.nfilters = nfilters
    self.kernel_size = kernel_size
    self.stride = stride
    self.pool_size = pool_size
    self.leakyrelu_slope = leakyrelu_slope
    self.dropfrac = dropc
    self.bnorm = bnorm
  
  def __call__(self, x):
    x = Conv2D(self.nfilters, kernel_size=self.kernel_size, 
               strides=self.stride, padding='same')(x)
    x = LeakyReLU(self.leakyrelu_slope)(x)
    if (self.dropfrac > 0.0): 
      x = Dropout(self.dropfrac)(x)
    if (self.bnorm):
      x = BatchNormalization()(x)
    x = MaxPool2D(self.pool_size)(x)
    return x

class dense_Layers:

  def __init__(self, nunits, leakyrelu_slope=0.1, dropd=0.0, bnorm=False):
    self.nunits = nunits
    self.leakyrelu_slope = leakyrelu_slope 
    self.dropfrac = dropd
    self.bnorm = bnorm

  def __call__(self, x):
    x = Dense(self.nunits)(x)
    x = LeakyReLU(self.leakyrelu_slope)(x)
    if (self.dropfrac > 0.0):
      x = Dropout(self.dropfrac)(x)
    if (self.bnorm):
      x = BatchNormalization()(x)
    return x

def LNmodel(in_shape, conv_filters, dense_filters, kernel_size, num_classes, lr,
            stride=1, pool_size=2, leakyrelu_slope=0.1, dropc=0.0, dropd=0.0, bnorm=False):

  in_shape = X_train.shape[1:]
  i = Input(shape=in_shape)
  for ncl, nconvfilters in enumerate(conv_filters):
    if (ncl==0):
      x = conv_Layers(nconvfilters, kernel_size,
                      stride, pool_size, leakyrelu_slope, dropc, bnorm)(i)
    else:
      x = conv_Layers(nconvfilters, kernel_size,
                      stride, pool_size, leakyrelu_slope, dropc, bnorm)(x)

  x = Flatten()(x)

  for ndl, ndunits in enumerate(dense_filters):
    x = dense_Layers(ndunits, leakyrelu_slope, dropd, bnorm)(x)

  x = Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')(x)

  ln_model  = Model(inputs=i, outputs=x)
  adam = optimizers.Adam(lr=lr)
  ln_model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=adam, metrics=['accuracy'])
  return ln_model

#Plotting the confusion matrix of Model_1
plt.subplots(figsize=(22,7)) #set the size of the plot 

def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    """
    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    """
    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = range(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]

    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, cm[i, j],
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

# Predict the values from the validation dataset
Y_pred = model.predict(X_val)
# Convert predictions classes to one hot vectors 
Y_pred_classes = np.argmax(Y_pred,axis = 1) 
# Convert validation observations to one hot vectors
Y_true = np.argmax(Y_val,axis = 1) 
# compute the confusion matrix
confusion_mtx = confusion_matrix(Y_true, Y_pred_classes) 
# plot the confusion matrix
plot_confusion_matrix(confusion_mtx, classes = range(len(classes)))

                          normalize=False,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    """
    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    """
    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]

    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, cm[i, j],
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

Data Augmentation

Since the data is an imbalanced data as earlier highlighted, we will therefore explore data augmentation and build another model for possible improved performance. Although this will not address the imbalance in the data but is expected to help reduce the overfitting seen in the earlier 3 models built.

Model Evaluation¶

As we can see, Model 1, 2 and Model 3 seem not to be generalizing well because they all overfit and do not have a good holdout set of Accuracy. Let us therefore check the performance of Model_4 on our test set as the model gives the highest accuracy so far.

Conclusion¶

Model_4 which is built on augmented data shows the best accuracy, generalises well and has the least misclassified plants as shown in the confusion matrix. We are therefore going with this model. However, all the models built struggle to identify Black-grass as it is often wrongly classified as Loose Silky-bent. There is therefore still scope for improvement in the test accuracy of the CNN model chosen here.
